      <body>
        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0524.jpg" n="part4_p050.jpg" xml:id="img_0050" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p050.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_50_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>sʼil mʼa fait
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>-ene¬
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>comes from the Creator-God, something arbitrary and not identical with the GOOD creation itself.
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>Now I cannot go into the history of dogma here, but we shouldn’t go in an interest which
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>sometimes appears in radical Protestantism [such] as that of the whole Barthian Neo-Ormodox
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/> Verhool. We shouldn’t, in this interest, make God a tyrant, His law heteronomous, because that
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_50_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>only would have the consequence that we have to resist Him and to look for a God who is greater
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>than this God, as Marcion and his friends did.
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>Now if this is clear, then we can go on and say: there is no OTHER external authority
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>on the categorical—or let mebringing call it the moral--imperative, either. That which has
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/> B H
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>replaced God, in modern positivistie thinking, is society: the moral imperative comes from society.
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>The profoundest form, I think, in which this has been done is done by Friedrich Nietzsche who, in his
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>description of theürnesis of conscience, describes it as the internalization of the rules of a ruling
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>class, which can maintain its rule only if the laws are not forced from outside only, but also put
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>into the internal situation, into the internal feeling of man, made a matter of conscience of everybody,
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_2_tl_11" n="N011"/>which even works if the policeman is around the next corner.
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_50_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>Now this is the main point of this theory, which trees to show that the experience of
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>imperative ("you HALL, though OUGHTEST, to do this!") is the result of an
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>the moral
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>internalized policeman, the policeman in ourselves. But this policeman in ourselves is a product of a
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>ruling group which cleverly realized that its control of society is safeiently if ITS interests are affirmed
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>by the conscience of the subjects.
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>Monsieur Mounard, et le Comte de
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>Cela nʼentraîne
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>lʼhonneur de lʼautre vieusement beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>dʼavoir lʼautre
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>dans les
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>dire une
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>Monsieur Mounard, et
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_14" n="N014"/>Monsieur Mounard, et
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_15" n="N015"/>de vous
               <lb facs="#facs_50_tr_1_tl_16" n="N016"/>Monsieur,
            </p>
            
